{
  "_doc": {
    "purpose": "The RIVALS table. aliases.json solves one axis of collision (one algorithm, many names); this file solves the other (one problem, many phrasings). Each entry's `d` is a specific problem phrase chosen to carry the trade-off ('Negative-edge shortest paths' is exactly why you reach for Bellman-Ford). That specificity is worth keeping, but it fragments the problem axis: Dijkstra and Bellman-Ford stopped looking like rivals because their phrases differ. This registry maps many phrases onto one canonical problem, so rival lookup is mechanical without flattening the phrasing.",
    "schema": "Every key except those starting with underscore is a slug (lowercase, hyphens) that will become a stable /problem/<slug> URL. Value: { label: display name, phrases: [exact `d` values from atlas entries] }. A phrase must match at least one live entry (check fails on dead phrases) and may be claimed by exactly one problem.",
    "rivalsRule": "Two entries are RIVALS when they resolve to the same problem, either through this registry or by sharing an identical `d`. Unit pages name two or three rivals with a when-to-prefer line; see the rivals doctrine in CLAUDE.md and docs/ATLAS.md.",
    "growthNote": "Partial coverage is fine and expected. An unregistered phrase simply stands alone (or clusters with exact matches of itself). `npm run check` prints the largest unregistered phrases as a planning queue, so this file grows from evidence rather than guesswork."
  },

